         <abstract>
            <p>We introduce fast Fourier transform algorithms (FFTs) designed for fused multiply-add architectures. We show how to compute a complex discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of length n = 2&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt; with 8/3nm - 16/9 n + 2 - 2/9(-1)&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt; real multiply-adds. For real input, this algorithm uses 4/3nm - 17/9n + 3 - 1/9(-1)&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt; real multiply-adds. We also describe efficient multidimensional FFTs. These algorithms can be used to compute the DFT of an n × n array of complex data using 14/3n&lt;sup&gt;2m&lt;/sup&gt; - 4/3n&lt;sup&gt;2&lt;/sup&gt; - 4/9n(-1)&lt;sup&gt;m&lt;/sup&gt; + 16/9 real multiply-adds. For each problem studied, the number of multiply-adds that our algorithms use is a record upper bound for the number required.</p>
          </abstract>
